        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Real</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">log</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≠</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">log</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">3</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>This seems like a straightforward problem. However, common tactics like <code>exact?</code>, <code>simp?</code>, and <code>norm_num</code> don’t solve it. I know it can be deduced from the fact that <code>log</code> is injective, but is there a simpler or more direct way to prove it?</p>",
        "id": 483091762,
        "sender_full_name": "Yiming Fu",
        "timestamp": 1731954203
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"749369\">peli</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Logarithmic.20Functions/near/483091762\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I know it can be deduced from the fact that <code>log</code> is injective</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That seems like a very direct way to prove it to me. <code>apply Real.log_injOn_pos.ne</code> will do almost all the work for you</p>",
        "id": 483092781,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1731954535
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(found by typing <code>apply Real.log_inj</code>, letting autocomplete finish the theorem name, and then guessing <code>.ne</code>)</p>",
        "id": 483092867,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1731954566
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for your suggestion. But I still need to verify that <code>2∈Set.Ioi</code> and <code>3∈Set.Ioi</code>. It feels a bit complex. Is there a more direct approach, perhaps something more computational?\"</p>",
        "id": 483095092,
        "sender_full_name": "Yiming Fu",
        "timestamp": 1731955320
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think <code>norm_num</code> or <code>aesop</code> can dispatch those side goals</p>",
        "id": 483095854,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1731955403
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you really wanted a computational approach, I guess you could use something like <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Real.log_two_lt_d9#doc\">docs#Real.log_two_lt_d9</a>, and add some similar theorems for <code>Real.log 3</code></p>",
        "id": 483096579,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1731955475
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, that is a good way. I just want to know if there’s a way to calculate this directly, though it seems Lean4 doesn’t support it yet.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Real</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">log</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≠</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">log</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">3</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Real</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">log_injOn_pos</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">ne</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;;&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">norm_num</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 483097298,
        "sender_full_name": "Yiming Fu",
        "timestamp": 1731955575
    },
